To determine the present value of a future amount discounted at a given interest rate, we can use the formula for present value:

$$
\begin{equation*}
    \text{PV} = \frac{\text{FV}}(1 + r)^n\,,
\end{equation*}
$$

where:
- PV is the present value;
- FV is the future value;
- *r* is the discount rate or interest rate per period;
- *n* is the number of periods.

Given that you will receive $75 in 7 years with a 9% discount rate (or 0.09 as a decimal), we can plug these values into the formula:

$$
\begin{align*}
    \text{PV} & = \frac{\text{\textdollar}75}{(1 + 0.09)^7}\\\\
    & \approx \text{\textdollar}43.27\,.
\end{align*}
$$

So, the present value of the $\text{\textdollar}75$ you will receive in 7 years at a 9% discount rate is approximately $\boxed{\text{\textdollar}43.27}$.
